# Intersection Observer (Spy Scroll) - Safari

Safari handles `IntersectionObserver` differently from Chrome. Use pixel-based values for reliable behaviour.

## Rules

1. **rootMargin in pixels.** Safari's percentage-based `rootMargin` is unreliable. Use pixel values computed from `window.innerHeight` instead of percentages (e.g. `-${topPx}px 0px -${bottomPx}px 0px`).
2. **Last section.** Ensure the last section (e.g. "Other") is included in the active-zone logic. Use viewport bounds (top/bottom threshold in px) so scroll-to-bottom highlights the last section.

## Examples

```typescript
// BAD: Percentage rootMargin (unreliable in Safari)
rootMargin: "-10% 0px -10% 0px"

// GOOD: Pixel values from viewport
function getRootMarginPx(): string {
  const topPx = Math.round(window.innerHeight * 0.1);
  const bottomPx = Math.round(window.innerHeight * 0.1);
  return `-${topPx}px 0px -${bottomPx}px 0px`;
}
```

```typescript
// GOOD: Bottom threshold for last section
const BOTTOM_THRESHOLD_PX = 80;
if (scrollTop + clientHeight >= scrollHeight - BOTTOM_THRESHOLD_PX) {
  return lastSectionId;
}
```

**Reference:** `shared/hooks/useActiveSection.ts` - `getRootMarginPx()`, `getActiveZoneBounds()`, `BOTTOM_THRESHOLD_PX`
